nodes.text: DOT should set maximum tarmac delay trigger.
AFCHF(388): DOT should set maximum tarmac delay trigger.
Annot: DOT should set maximum tarmac delay trigger.
It then should apply to ALL AIRLINES and ALL CLASSES of AIRCRAFT.
AFCHF(388): It then should apply to ALL AIRLINES and ALL CLASSES of AIRCRAFT.
Annot: It then should apply to ALL AIRLINES and ALL CLASSES of AIRCRAFT.
The airlines need to make a legal committment (contract of carriage).
AFCHF(388): The airlines need to make a legal committment (contract of carriage).
Annot: The airlines need to make a legal committment (contract of carriage).
Deplaneing without CBP screening IS a viable option.
AFCHF(388): Deplaneing without CBP screening IS a viable option.
Annot: Deplaneing without CBP screening IS a viable option.
As a military member, I have done this many times during overseas contract flights.
AFCHF(388): As a military member, I have done this many times during overseas contract flights.
Annot: As a military member, I have done this many times during overseas contract flights.
I realize this is customs rather than airport security, but the concept is the same.
AFCHF(388): I realize this is customs rather than airport security, but the concept is the same.
Annot: I realize this is customs rather than airport security, but the concept is the same.
Allow passengers to deplane during gate holds,
AFCHF(388): Allow passengers to deplane during gate holds,
Annot: Allow passengers to deplane during gate holds,
but require them to remain in the immediate area.
AFCHF(388): but require them to remain in the immediate area.
Annot: but require them to remain in the immediate area.
This is no different than an openended delay prior to boarding.
AFCHF(388): This is no different than an openended delay prior to boarding.
Annot: This is no different than an openended delay prior to boarding.
I think it's important to stress the real reason that aircraft is not returning to the gate.
golff4fun(439): I think it's important to stress the real reason that aircraft is not returning to the gate.
Annot: I think it's important to stress the real reason that aircraft is not returning to the gate.
Once the aircraft pulls away from the jetway, the crew is on the clock.
golff4fun(439): Once the aircraft pulls away from the jetway, the crew is on the clock.
Annot: Once the aircraft pulls away from the jetway, the crew is on the clock.
They are not being paid while sitting at a gate.
golff4fun(439): They are not being paid while sitting at a gate.
Annot: They are not being paid while sitting at a gate.
And 3 hours is too long to keep people on a grounded airplane.
golff4fun(439): And 3 hours is too long to keep people on a grounded airplane.
Annot: And 3 hours is too long to keep people on a grounded airplane.
Yes, most airlines pay flight crew members scheduled flight time or actual time away from the gate whichever is more.
JetJock(516): Yes, most airlines pay flight crew members scheduled flight time or actual time away from the gate whichever is more.
Annot: Yes, most airlines pay flight crew members scheduled flight time or actual time away from the gate whichever is more.
Eg. if a flight is scheduled for 2 hours "block to block" (from/to the gate) but it takes 3 to fly it, the crew gets 3.
JetJock(516): Eg. if a flight is scheduled for 2 hours "block to block" (from/to the gate) but it takes 3 to fly it, the crew gets 3.
Annot: Eg. if a flight is scheduled for 2 hours "block to block" (from/to the gate) but it takes 3 to fly it, the crew gets 3.
If the flight leaves that gate and returns 2.5 hours later, most airlines only pay that crew either the 2.0 scheduled (if it cancels) or much less.
JetJock(516): If the flight leaves that gate and returns 2.5 hours later, most airlines only pay that crew either the 2.0 scheduled (if it cancels) or much less.
Annot: If the flight leaves that gate and returns 2.5 hours later, most airlines only pay that crew either the 2.0 scheduled (if it cancels) or much less.
For most crewmembers, the notion that 1 hour at the gate, 2.5 hours of sitting on that taxiway and only get paid for 2 is not very palatable.
JetJock(516): For most crewmembers, the notion that 1 hour at the gate, 2.5 hours of sitting on that taxiway and only get paid for 2 is not very palatable.
Annot: For most crewmembers, the notion that 1 hour at the gate, 2.5 hours of sitting on that taxiway and only get paid for 2 is not very palatable.
Whereas sitting for 2.5 hours then fly 2 totals 4.5.
JetJock(516): Whereas sitting for 2.5 hours then fly 2 totals 4.5.
Annot: Whereas sitting for 2.5 hours then fly 2 totals 4.5.
It is mostly the pay structure of pilots/flight attendants that poorly designed.
JetJock(516): It is mostly the pay structure of pilots/flight attendants that poorly designed.
Annot: It is mostly the pay structure of pilots/flight attendants that poorly designed.
Most people would balk at the notion of working 4.5 hours and getting paid for 2.
JetJock(516): Most people would balk at the notion of working 4.5 hours and getting paid for 2.
Annot: Most people would balk at the notion of working 4.5 hours and getting paid for 2.
The ground delay limitation, has, well, it's limitations.
JetJock(516): The ground delay limitation, has, well, it's limitations.
Annot: The ground delay limitation, has, well, it's limitations.
If we were in preregulation days where an airline was making money with only 60% of the seats filled, flights canceling due to the 3 hour limit would not be much of a problem.
JetJock(516): If we were in preregulation days where an airline was making money with only 60% of the seats filled, flights canceling due to the 3 hour limit would not be much of a problem.
Annot: If we were in preregulation days where an airline was making money with only 60% of the seats filled, flights canceling due to the 3 hour limit would not be much of a problem.
What is a problem is flights that are now being canceled because of the new rule
JetJock(516): What is a problem is flights that are now being canceled because of the new rule
Annot: What is a problem is flights that are now being canceled because of the new rule
and virtually no seats available on subsequent flights to accommodate those passengers.
JetJock(516): and virtually no seats available on subsequent flights to accommodate those passengers.
Annot: and virtually no seats available on subsequent flights to accommodate those passengers.
If the ground delays are due to ATC, weather, VIP movement (president in the area) then passengers will not be, as a rule, given cancellation perks since they are beyond the control of the company.

JetJock(516): If the ground delays are due to ATC, weather, VIP movement (president in the area) then passengers will not be, as a rule, given cancellation perks since they are beyond the control of the company.

Annot: If the ground delays are due to ATC, weather, VIP movement (president in the area) then passengers will not be, as a rule, given cancellation perks since they are beyond the control of the company.
If the air conditioning, and restrooms are functioning properly and there are plenty of beverages and snacks on board then that maximum number of hours should be flexible.
JetJock(516): If the air conditioning, and restrooms are functioning properly and there are plenty of beverages and snacks on board then that maximum number of hours should be flexible.
Annot: If the air conditioning, and restrooms are functioning properly and there are plenty of beverages and snacks on board then that maximum number of hours should be flexible.
I would be curious to hear from people that had their flight cancel due to the 3 hour limit and how the airlines handled them after that.
JetJock(516): I would be curious to hear from people that had their flight cancel due to the 3 hour limit and how the airlines handled them after that.
Annot: I would be curious to hear from people that had their flight cancel due to the 3 hour limit and how the airlines handled them after that.
My guess this rule will cause greater damage to air travel then the occasional extended ground hold on an airplane with poor air conditioning or nonfunctioning lavatories.
JetJock(516): My guess this rule will cause greater damage to air travel then the occasional extended ground hold on an airplane with poor air conditioning or nonfunctioning lavatories.
Annot: My guess this rule will cause greater damage to air travel then the occasional extended ground hold on an airplane with poor air conditioning or nonfunctioning lavatories.

if the airplane is comfortable and exceeding the 3 hour limit would cancel the flight with no hotel or meal compensation, would exceeding the 3 hours be ok and if so what would be a reasonable number above 3 be?
